The Cartesian product of two sets A and B, denoted as A x B, is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of A and b is an element of B.

Let's calculate A x B and B x A:

A x B = {(a, b) | a ∈ A, b ∈ B}
= {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}

B x A = {(b, a) | b ∈ B, a ∈ A}
= {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)}

As we can see, A x B and B x A are not equal:

A x B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)} ≠ {(3, 1), (3, 2), (4, 1), (4, 2)} = B x A

This shows that the Cartesian product of two sets is not commutative.
